    "reasoning": "We need to find v = a_N(0) from the base-b(x) representation of P(x) = x^{2015}+x^{2014}+...+x+1, where b(x)=x^2+x+1. The representation is P(x) = ∑_{k=0}^N a_k(x) b(x)^k with deg(a_k) < 2. The degree of P is 2015, so the highest power N satisfies 2N+1 = 2015, hence N=1007 and a_N(x) is linear. Write a_N(x)=Ax+B. The leading term of P is x^{2015}. The leading term of a_N(x)b(x)^N is A x^{2N+1} = A x^{2015}, so A=1. To ensure the remainder after subtracting a_N(x)b(x)^N has degree < 2N=2014, we cancel the x^{2014} term. The coefficient of x^{2014} in P is 1. In (x+B)b(x)^N, the coefficient of x^{2014} is N+B. Thus 1 - (N+B)=0 => B=1-N = -1006. So a_N(x)= x-1006, and v = a_N(0) = -1006. Then v+1012 = -1006+1012 = 6, so we consider a regular hexagon.\n\nWe need the number of triangulations of a regular hexagon (with non-intersecting diagonals) such that in every triangle, at least one side is a side of the hexagon. Total triangulations of a hexagon are C_4=14. The condition fails if a triangle has all three sides as diagonals. In a hexagon, the only such triangles are ACE and BDF (vertices every other). There is exactly one triangulation containing ACE (diagonals AC, CE, EA) and one containing BDF (diagonals BD, DF, FB). These two triangulations violate the condition. All other triangulations satisfy it. Thus the number is 14 - 2 = 12.",
    "answer": "12"
}
